Which country is the best at solving Rubik's cubes?¶

An analysis by Syam Angalakuditi¶

Introduction¶

Unless you've been living under a rock, you've probably heard of the notorious Rubik's Cube. And if you've solved it, congratulations! There's actually a massive community of "cubers" that participate in competitions for solving not only the classic 3x3 cube, but all sorts of similar puzzles, as fast as they can. These competitions are organized by the World Cube Association, also known as the WCA. Puzzles can be as small as a 2x2x2 cube, as big as a 7x7x7 cube, or even as confusing as this monstrosity, known as the Megaminx. And if solving it with your eyes open is too easy, there's also blindfolded solving. In fact, the world record for Multi-Blind solving (memorizing multiple 3x3 cubes and then solving ALL of them blindfolded) is 62/67 cubes solved correctly in under an hour!

People all over the world love to participate in these competitions. And while not every country is of equal standing, some countries are without a doubt more ahead of the game than others. So can we rank countries based on how good they are at cubing? How do we even begin to do that?

Let's look at the Results table. This will have information on every solve recorded at every WCA competition, for each competitor and event. Data is entered and verified by WCA officials after each competition, but just to be sure, let's check for duplicates.

2) Cleaning up the data¶

2i) Solve formats¶

The 'personCountryId' column is now duplicated, so drop that.

Solves are recorded in different formats, depending on the event and the number of competitors present at that round. Most solve sessions are calculated one of two ways: the average of 5 solves (with the best and worst solve excluded from the average calculation), or the mean of 3 solves. These are denoted by the formatIds 'a' or 'm', respectively. But for some bigger cubes, such as a 7x7x7 cube, the best of X solves is calculated, where X is 1, 2, or 3 (this is also its formatId in the table).

The Magic and Master Magic no longer have WCA competitions held for them because they were too simple of puzzles with too few distinct solutions to make it worth competing for, so we will drop those rows. Here's a list of all events, and their corresponding id used throughout the datasets. Additionally, since blindfolded solves are encoded differently with multiple variables, we will exclude those from our features. Below is a list of events with their respective ids used throughout this analysis.

2ii) Invalid solves¶

From the WCA Results Database Export, values that are 0 or negative can be interpreted as follows:

  • The value -1 means DNF (Did Not Finish).
  • The value -2 means DNS (Did Not Start).
  • The value 0 means "no result". For example a result in a best-of-3 round has a value of 0 for the value4, value5, and average fields.

Additionally, all solve time values are given in centiseconds (100 centiseconds = 1 second), so convert those to seconds. For shorthand notation, the following denotation will be used from hereon out:

  • Average of 5: Ao5
  • Mean of 3: Mo3
  • Best of X: BoX

For the sake of convenience, we will put our BoX data into the 'average' column as well to make later processing simpler.

In [7]:
#Format ids of Ao5/Mo3 solves
avg_ids = ['a', 'm']

#anything with a 0, -1, or -2 in the "best" column means that session is invalid (no matter what formatId), so filter on that first
df = df[(df['best'] > 0)]

#doing isin() a lot is slow so make a boolean column for if a solve session is an Ao5/Mo3 or BoX
df['isAvg'] = df['formatId'].isin(avg_ids)

#Put best data in average column to make later processing easier
df.loc[~df.isAvg, 'average'] = df.loc[~df.isAvg, 'best']

#if a row's 'average' col is <= 0, it's an invalid solve session; remove it.
df = df[df['average'] > 0]

#Times are given in centiseconds; divide by 100
df['average'] = df['average'].apply(lambda x: x / 100)
df['best'] = df['best'].apply(lambda x: x / 100)

df.drop(columns='isAvg', inplace=True)
df

2iii) Country Codes¶

The country codes given are in ISO-2, but our GeoJson data is mapped using the country's ISO-3166 Alpha 3 (or ISO-3 for short). To account for this we will convert all ISO-2 values to their ISO-3 equivalents.

In [8]:
#GeoJSON uses id "-99" for Kosovo
def to_iso3(x):
    try:
        c = pycountry.countries.get(alpha_2=x).alpha_3
        return c
    except Exception:
        return "-99"

df['iso3'] = df['iso2'].apply(lambda x: to_iso3(x))

#Namibia is missing ISO Alpha-2 in WCA data, so fill in ISO Alpha-3 manually
df.loc[df['id_country'] == "Namibia", 'iso3'] = "NAM"

Transform data¶

Our data is heavily skewed to the right, which makes sense if you think about it. Many people start out as novice cubers, but get bored before they improve their times. That would definitely cause a lot more data to the right, i.e. a positive skew. Let's apply a log transformation to our data to make it more centered.

In [10]:

3ii) Data by country¶

Let's observe some statistics by country. While the log transformation did help in normalizing the data, they are still quite skewed with a non-insignificant amount of outliers. Our mean would be sensitive to that, so the map below uses the median log(Time) for each country.

We can see that in general, the lowest median 3x3x3 solve times mostly lie in European countries. Additionally, despite their large populations, China and the United States have quite low 3x3x3 solve times.

Scraping data¶

But in order to make a ranking model, we need training data somehow! Obtaining a ranking from our datasets would be an arduous process involving multiple DataFrame transformation and operations; fortunately the WCA provides country rankings on their website for each event's average and single. Let's scrape that website and rank the countries. As opposed to before, in these rankings we will consider blindfolded events as well to get the most accurate ACTUAL ranking as possible. We will get the ranking of countries for each event's single and average (except Multi-Blind, because those are only done as singles) and assign all the columns a temporary rank 1-n. Then, we will find the mean rank for each country using that temporary rank, sort them by mean rank, and re-rank the rows 1-n. In order to merge with our data, we will also need to convert each country's name to an ISO Alpha-3 code.

In [15]:
#Names of continents and other rows to remove
remove = ['World', 'Europe', 'North America', 'South America', 'Asia', 'Africa', 'Oceania']
base_url = "https://www.worldcubeassociation.org/results/rankings/"

rankdf = pd.DataFrame()

evs = [x for x in a if x not in ['magic', 'mmagic', '333mbo']]

#For each event
for ev in evs:
    if ev == "333mbf":
        url_single = base_url + f"{ev}/single?show=by+region"
        dfs = pd.read_html(url_single)[0]
        
        dfs = dfs[~dfs['Region'].isin(remove)]
        dfs = dfs.dropna(how='all')
        dfs = dfs.rename(columns={'Region': ev})
        
        rankdf = pd.concat([rankdf, dfs[ev]], axis=1)
    else:
        #Get region rankings for single and average
        url_single = base_url + f"{ev}/single?show=by+region"
        url_avg = base_url + f"{ev}/average?show=by+region"

        dfs = pd.read_html(url_single)[0]
        dfa = pd.read_html(url_avg)[0]

        dfs = dfs[~dfs['Region'].isin(remove)]
        dfs = dfs.dropna(how='all')
        dfs = dfs.rename(columns={'Region': ev+'_s'})

        dfa = dfa[~dfa['Region'].isin(remove)]
        dfa = dfa.dropna(how='all')
        dfa = dfa.rename(columns={'Region': ev+'_a'})

        if rankdf.empty:
            rankdf = pd.concat([dfs[ev+'_s'], dfa[ev+'_a']], axis=1)
        else:
            rankdf = pd.concat([rankdf, dfs[ev+'_s'], dfa[ev+'_a']], axis=1)
        

#Some columns have leading NaNs, so push columns upwards if they do
for col in rankdf:
    while pd.isna(rankdf[col].iat[0]):
        rankdf[col] = rankdf[col].shift(-1)

#Now each country is ordered correctly for each event, assign a temp rank to aggregate on (1-n)
rankdf['rank'] = np.arange(1, 155)

#Define every ranking category
cols = list(rankdf.columns)
cols.remove('rank')
cols.remove('333_s')

#Since 3x3 Single has the most countries for its' data, we will start rank data with that
rdata = rankdf.pivot_table(values='rank', columns='333_s', aggfunc='mean').T.reset_index()
rdata = rdata.rename(columns={'333_s': 'country'})

#For each ranking category, create a column of ranks for each country and add it to rdata
for c in cols:
    d = rankdf.pivot_table(values='rank', columns=c, aggfunc='first').T.reset_index()
    rdata = rdata.merge(d, how='left', left_on='country', right_on=c, suffixes=(None, c)).fillna(150)
    rdata = rdata.drop(columns=c)

#Compute mean rank across row (for each country)
rdata['overall_rank'] = rdata.iloc[:, 1:].mean(axis=1)

#Drop extraneous rows, sort by rank, and rerank from 1-n (because previous mean operation produces floats)
rdata = rdata.drop(labels=['rank'] + ["rank"+c for c in cols], axis=1)
rdata = rdata.sort_values('overall_rank')
rdata['overall_rank'] = np.arange(1, 151)

#Define iso-3 conversion
def to_iso32(c):
    try:
        x = pycountry.countries.search_fuzzy(c)[0].alpha_3
        return x
    except Exception:
        return "INVALID"
        
#Perform conversion
rdata['iso3'] = rdata['country'].apply(lambda x: to_iso32(x))

#Incorrect/invalid values; fill in manually
rdata.loc[rdata.country == "Macau", 'iso3'] = "MAC"
rdata.loc[rdata.country == "Cte d'Ivoire", 'iso3'] = "CIV"
rdata.loc[rdata.country == "Democratic Republic of the Congo", 'iso3'] = "COD"
rdata.loc[rdata.country == "Republic of Korea", 'iso3'] = "KOR"
rdata.loc[rdata.country == "Kosovo", 'iso3'] = "-99"
rdata

Now we can merge our scraped data with our times. Since we have some missing values, let's encode them with very high or 0 values accordingly so that our model can distinguish them.

4) Hypothesis Testing¶

4i) Random Forests¶

Now that we have our data, how accurately can it be ranked? As can be seen, we had to manually input a lot of missing values. Fortunately, there are learning models that can handle missing data and unexpected values quite well. One of those models is the Random Forest. Since our input data is passed in sorted by rank, we have to be careful on how our data is split into training and testing sets. To counteract this, we will use a shuffle split, which shuffles the indices of the data to give more random splits (and therefore, more accurate predictions). Since our data has relatively few rows, we will do 15 different splits. Assume a significance level of 0.05.

Null Hypothesis:¶

The model cannot accurately rank the data. To be more specific, there is no correlation between the actual rankings and predicted rankings outputted by the model.

Alternative Hypothesis:¶

The model can accurately rank the data. In other words, there is a correlation between the actual rankings and predicted rankings outputted by the model.

In [17]:
# Split the data into training and test sets
X = data.drop(columns=['country', 'overall_rank', 'iso3'])
y = data['overall_rank']

rs = ShuffleSplit(n_splits=10, test_size=0.5)

actual = []
predicted = []

for i, (train_index, test_index) in enumerate(rs.split(X)):
    X_train, X_test = X.iloc[train_index], X.iloc[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_index], y.iloc[test_index]
    
    rfc = RandomForestClassifier().fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_out = rfc.predict(X_test)

    actual.extend(list(y_test))
    predicted.extend(list(y_out))


vals = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(actual, predicted)), columns =['Actual', 'Predicted'])
sns.lmplot(vals, x='Actual', y='Predicted')

res = stats.spearmanr(actual, predicted)
print("Correlation:", res.correlation)
print("p-value:", res.pvalue)

Correlation: 0.9026570354876895
p-value: 4.1298053201787615e-276

4ii) Histogram Gradient Boosting¶

As we can see, the data has quite a strong correlation. Since our p-value is very small (may not be exactly 0, but very close to 0.00), we've already successfully rejected the null hypothesis, proving that our Random Forest Classifier model can accurately rank data! But upon examining the scatterplot, it seems like some of the middle values are not predicted very well. Many points of data seem clumped up towards either end of the line, and the rest of the points are rather sparsely distributed. This may indicate the model can predict extreme values more accurately, but it's unfair to most countries.

Let's try another model to see if it can predict middle rankings more accurately. The HistGradientBoostingClassifier from the 'sklearn' library is supposed to handle missing values especially well, so we will proceed with that.

Conclusion¶

Purely visually speaking, we can notice a pretty significant improvement over our previous model! The correlation coefficient is higher than before, and our p-value is still significantly low enough for us to reject the null hypothesis. But the Histogram Gradient Boosting classifier seems to predict middle values much more accurately. While it still has outliers, they are much more distinct and fewer in number than the predictions made by the Random Forest classifier. Additionally, it seems to predict lower ranked countries much more accurately (indicated by points closely adhering along the tail end of the regression line), which is an indication of the model's ability to handle missing/drop-in values quite well.

This is certainly some very interesting insight, as Random Forest classifiers are generally the recommended option for handling missing data. But as the analysis shows, selecting an appropriate model is very much dependent on the scenario that one is working with. A suitable follow-up analysis could involve ranking countries within continents. From the maps above, we could see that many countries in Europe are competitive, with some of the lowest median 3x3 times. On the other hand, many countries in Africa are missing data, which would definitely impede the overall accuracy of our model. Carrying out such an analysis could even give us insight on what other factors (possibly non-cubing related), if any, can play a role in ranking countries.
